comment.author: 70213421@N02
comment.text: Peter Zachary Lloyd was the clerk of the General Assembly in Philadelphia circa 1785-1792. His name is found as the clerk of the General Assembly in The debates in the several state conventions on the adoption of Federal Constitution as recommended by the General Convention at Philadelphia in 1787. He is listed as a lawyer of Delaware County admitted in August 1772, in Henry Graham Ashmead's History of Delaware County, Pennsylvania. The Historical Society of Pennsylvania has Lloyd's journal of the First Session of the House of Representatives of the Commonwealth of Pennsylvania 1790-1792. Lloyd appears also to have been a fairly early settler of land in central Pennsylvania on the Susquehanna River: he purchased land along with Mary Norris in the borough of Montoursville in 1777, in Lycoming County, PA near Williamsport. See this history of Lycoming County. This land had been purchased by Andrew (Henry) Montour in 1768. It was referred to as "Montour's Reserve" and comprised 880 acres including the Indian settlements of Ostuagy and Ostonwakin. The land was then sold to Peter Zachary Lloyd and Mary Norris, and subsequently the patent for the land was issued to them in 1785. Also see this account.

[Dated early 17th-century ownership inscription of Johannes Sigefridus Cuperus, also known as Johannes or Johannes Seijbert Cuperus and Johannes Fabricius, recording the gift of this book from an Eberhardus Aschendorffius. According to this genealogical website, Cuperus was born ca. 1595 in Dillenburg, Germany, and was ordained a Reformed minister. From 1607-1610 he seems to have served at Grijpskerk in Groningen, the Netherlands (cf. this website run by the RHC Groninger Archieven), until he was dismissed for blasphemy. Cuperus appealed and was eventually cleared and assigned to Gasselte in Drenthe in 1611, where he served until 1630; cf. the monument pictured here. He represented Drenthe at the Synod of Dort in 1618. His tenure at Gasselte was occasionally turbulent: in 1622 he was fined for getting into a drunken fight with another minister; in 1623 he was called to account for his son Bernhardus's preaching without license; in 1624 he was accused of sanctioning an irregular marriage. In 1630 he was assigned to Zuidlaren in Drenthe, but did not prove a popular figure there. His predecessor in the post accused him of adultery; though sentenced to death, Cuperus was merely flogged and deposed in 1631. In 1634 he removed to the Palatinate in Germany; nothing further is known of him.]

His tenure at Gasselte was occasionally turbulent: in 1622 he was fined for getting into a drunken fight with another minister; in 1623 he was called to account for his son Bernhardus's preaching without license; in 1624 he was accused of sanctioning an irregular marriage. In 1630 he was assigned to Zuidlaren in Drenthe, but did not prove a popular figure there. His predecessor in the post accused him of adultery; though sentenced to death, Cuperus was merely flogged and deposed in 1631. In 1634 he removed to the Palatinate in Germany; nothing further is known of him.]

comment.text: Birgit Wiedl notes that the Eselritt (ass-ride), like the Sauritt (sow-ride), "is the typical feature of a type of pamphlet that is known as Schandbild or Schmähbrief ('defamatory picture/letter') that ... show the person(s) they are directed against as riding backwards; if groups of people are depicted, they might also engage in the 'typical' habit of occupying themselves with the animal's behind, shoving seals or money pouches into its hindquarters, or devouring its excrement" ("Laughing at the Beast" in Laughter in the Middle Ages and Early Modern Times, ed. A. Classen (Berlin: De Gruyter, 2010), p. 351). Donkeys are commonly depicted eating thistles; in the 16th century, this image also becomes emblematic of miserliness or the failure to appreciate the good things in one's possession: cf. emblem 86 in Andrea Alciati's Emblemata. (The anagram "Nasus/As(i)nus," used in this work, may also have influenced the choice of mount.) The pigs pursuing the donkey's droppings require no further comment. The rider is tonsured and dressed as a friar and bears a shield which identifies him as Johannes Nas. The upper portion of the shield shows a pair of scissors, three needles, and a thimble. Johannes Nas began life as a tailor and included a pair of shears on his episcopal arms; they are common in satirical depictions of him: cf. this image and this image. Here the tailor's tools are accompanied by a goat, negatively associated with lasciviousness and stubbornness (cf. Wiedl, p. 353, and the entry "Goat" in H.B. Werness, The Continuum Encyclopedia of Animal Symbolism in Art (New York: Continuum, 2006)).

comment.text: It looks like there are 2 separate inscriptions here: "A.W. Brunius 1869." There is an August W. Brunius in the CERL Thesaurus [1], with an activity date of 1823. He apparently lived in Lund, Sweden, and was a doctor there. Despite the gap between 1823 and 1869, he might be this person, given the mention of Lund in the next inscription. "Speratum. "J.J. Winslow: Lundini 16 Augusti Anno 1686. This first part of the second inscription apparently starts with a motto "Speratum," meaning "Hoping". The name "J. J. Winslow, Lund, 16 August 1868" is then given. I am assuming that "Lundini" is the Latin form of the city's name. Josias Simler, Theolog: Figurina Nat: 6 Novembr: 1530. Obyt. 2 July. 1576 At: 45. ann: 7. m. 26. d. Bucholtz: Ind: Gronol:" The second part of the second inscription is easier to decipher. It is simply the birth and death dates of Josias Simler, a Swiss theologian and classicist, author of the first book relating solely to the Alps. The same birth and death dates are given in his biography in Wikipedia. [2] It would seem then, that this book first found its way to Lund in the late 1600s, and was later acquired by A.W. Brunius there. [1] thesaurus.cerl.org/record/cnp00468929 [2] en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josias_Simmler

comment.author: 58584977@N05
comment.text: Regarding the identification of A.W. Brunius: According to a contemporary notice here, August W. Brunius, identified as "ProvincialLakaren" (i.e. provinsialläkare, district medical officer), married Anna Sophia Melén in Färjstaden on the island of Öland, Sweden, on 21 June 1826. (Anna Brunius died at Norrköping, Sweden, on 3 February 1875, just shy of her 70th birthday: her death notice gives her age as 69 years, 10 months and 26 days.) Swedish Wikipedia, in its article on the Brunius family, records an August Wilhelm Brunius (1795-1867), who served as provinsialläkare for Öland (dates confirmed in a footnote to an article in Samlaren 11 (1930), p. 72). This is almost certainly the August Wilhelm Brunius who defended a medical dissertation entitled De usu oxidi hydrargyrici in lue Venerica at Lunds universitet, Sweden, in 1823; in 1833 he submitted a ms. report on an outbreak of scarlet fever to the Sundhetskollegium (i.e. Board of Health). But if the date of our inscription is 1869, he cannot be our man. Another possibility is this Brunius's nephew, also named August Wilhelm Brunius, son of the architect, art historian and archaeologist Carl Georg Brunius (1793-1869). A Swedish army officer, he is listed as an under-ljötnant in the corps of engineers in 1865; in 1870 he was promoted to captain. In 1874 he was working in the Fortifikationsbiblioteket in Stockholm and in 1876 he edited a published catalog of its holdings, Katalog öfver Fortifikationsbiblioteket i Stockholm. By 1881, he was teaching at the royal military academy. Eventually he rose to the rank of major. He seems to have published a couple of books on military subjects (Om militära ekonomibyggnader i Danmark, Tyskland och Österrike in 1877 and Kavallerietablissementet å Ladugårdsgärdet in 1881) and one on Lund's cathedral, Några ord om Lunds domkyrka, in 1875. In 1893 he arranged to sell a collection of his father's ms. notes and drawings to the Kongliga Vitterhets-, Historie- och Antiqvitetsakademien in Stockholm (cf. its Månadsblad for that year; see also the notice in column 3 here). His provenance, sometimes in conjunction with his father's, does appear in various early printed works (e.g. this one and this one). On balance, I'm inclined to think our Brunius is this gentleman, not his uncle.

comment.text: Armorial bookplate of Edward Davenport. Arms: Argent, a chevron between three crosses-crosslet fitchée sable. Crest: A man's head couped at the shoulders and in profile proper, round the neck a halter or. Probably to be identified with Edward Davies Davenport (1778-1847) of Capesthorne, Chelford, Cheshire, UK. For the arms and a genealogical table in which this Edward Davenport is listed in the ultimate generation, see G. Ormerod, The History of the County Palatine and City of Chester, v. 2 (London: Lackington, Hughes, Harding, Mavor and Jones, 1819), p. 153-154. A more detailed and further-reaching genealogy of the family can be found at this website. Edward Davies Davenport appears to have been elected a member of the Society of Dilettanti in 1814 (cf. L. Cust and S. Colvin, History of the Society of Dilettanti (London: Macmillan, 1898), p. 286), which argues an interest in cultural matters (or at least wealth and clubbability; in 1816 he also became a member of Brooks's). In 1830 he married Caroline Anne Hurt (later notable as a friend and correspondent of Elizabeth Gaskell); their only child, Arthur, was born in 1832 and died unmarried in 1867. S. de Ricci, in Census of Medieval and Renaissance Italian Manuscripts in the United States and Canada (New York: Wilson, 1935), v. 1, p. 587, no. 476, records in a Venetian ms. owned by the University of Chicago an "ex-libris of Edward Davenport (ca. 1880)" which was subsequently sold in London (by Sotheby, Wilkinson & Hodge) on 10 May 1907 as part of the library of W. Bromley-Davenport (i.e. William Bromley-Davenport, 1821-1884, Edward's nephew and eventual heir); B. Cardon, in Manuscripts of the Speculum humanae salvationis in the Southern Netherlands (c. 1410-c. 1470) (Leuven: Peeters, 1996), records a similar chain of provenance for a Bruges ms. held by the Morgan Library: "ex-libris Edward Davenport (Time Deum et honora regem), Chelford, Cheshire (ca. 1860); Gruel, W. Bromley-Davenport sale, London, 10 May 1909 ..." (p. 408). I cannot reconcile the conjectured dates of these ex-libris with Edward Davies Davenport's 1847 date of death, but there also seems to be no other Edward Davenport with whom to associate them. Perhaps de Ricci and Cardon are just off by a few years?
